03987nam a22005295i 9780520919723DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19991999cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209197237 a10.1525/97805209197232doi  a(DE-B1597)648377  a(OCoLC)1414456169  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSOC0320002bisacsh1 aYamamoto, Traise, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMasking Selves, Making Subjects :bJapanese American Women, Identity, and the Body /cTraise Yamamoto; ed. by Traise Yamamoto. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (329 p.) :b1 black-and-white illustration  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Terms -- tIntroduction -- t1. "As natural as the partnership of sun and moon": Western Masculinity, Japanese Women and the Feminization of Japan -- t2. In/Visible Difference: Japanese American Female Subjectivity -- t3. "That other, private self": Masking in Nisei Women's Autobiography -- t4. Mothers, Daughters and die Trope of Maternal Absence in Japanese American Women's Fiction -- t5. Embodied Language: The Poetics of Mitsuye Yamada, Janice Mirikitani and Kimiko Hahn -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis sophisticated and comprehensive study is the first to situate Japanese American women's writing within theoretical contexts that provide a means of articulating the complex relationships between language and the body, gender and agency, nationalism and identity. Through an examination of post-World War II autobiographical writings, fiction, and poetry, Traise Yamamoto argues that these writers have employed the trope of masking—textually and psychologically—as a strategy to create an alternative discursive practice and to protect the self as subject.Yamamoto's range is broad, and her interdisciplinary approach yields richly textured, in-depth readings of a number of genres, including film and travel narrative. Looking at how the West has sexualized, infantilized, and feminized Japanese culture for over a century, she examines contemporary Japanese American women's struggle with this orientalist fantasy. Analyzing the various constraints and possibilities that these writers negotiate in order to articulate their differences, she shows how masking serves as a self-affirming discourse that dynamically interacts with mainstream culture's racial and sexual projections.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aGender Studies. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aYamamoto, Traise, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021034940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091972340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520919723423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520919723/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles